
[1]residence

   RES'IDENCE, n.

   1. The act of abiding or dwelling in a place for some continuance of
   time; as the residence of an American in France or Italy for a year.

   The confessor had often made considerable residences in Normandy.

   2. The place of abode; a dwelling; a habitation.

   Caprea had been - the residence of Tiberius for several years.

   3. That which falls to the bottom of liquors. Obs.

   4. In the canon and common law, the abode of a person or incumbent on
   his benefice; opposed to non-residence.
